article.headline: Vanderbilt 83, Michigan 63
article.story: NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Matt Freije scored 22 points before leaving the game with 5:41 remaining with a slight knee injury and Vanderbilt defeated Michigan 83-63 Saturday. Vanderbilt remained undefeated and won its fifth straight game while handing Michigan (4-1) its first loss of the season. The victory gave the Commodores a two-game sweep of Big Ten opponents this season after a victory over Indiana on Nov. 24. Scott Hundley had another strong game off the bench for Vanderbilt, scoring 13 points and grabbing eight rebounds. Julian Terrell added 10 points. Freije, the Southeastern Conference Preseason Player of the Year, was fouled attempting a three-point shot and left the game favoring his left knee. He was treated on the bench but did not return to the game. For Michigan, Bernard Robinson Jr. scored 14 points and had four assists. Vanderbilt dominated on the glass, out rebounding Michigan 42-24. Vanderbilt used a 16-3 run midway through the second half to take a commanding 70-49 lead. Hundley scored six straight points at one point during the run. Michigan never got with 15 points for the final 12 minutes of the game. Michigan guard Daniel Horton, the team's leading scorer, went down with a knee injury with 7:39 remaining in the first half and did not return until the second half. Michigan went on an 11-3 run following Horton's injury and closed Vanderbilt's lead to 34-31 late in the first half. Four points by Freije ended the first half scoring, giving Vanderbilt a 40-33 lead. Horton returned in the second half but did not score and finished with five points. The win snapped a five-game losing streak to Michigan and avenged the Wolverines' 70-66 win last year in Ann Arbor, Mich.
